---
import BaseLayout from "../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import "../../styles/global.css";
import ContactSection from "../../components/ContactSection.astro";
import Footer from "../../components/astro/Footer.astro";
import { AuroraOverlay } from "../../components/react/AuroraOverlay";
import { MobileNav } from "../../components/react/MobileNav";
import { Navbar } from "../../components/react/Navbar";
import { TableOfContents } from "../../components/react/compliance/TableOfContents";

import blogPosts from "../../lib/data/blog-posts.json";

export function getStaticPaths() {
	return blogPosts.map((post) => ({
		params: { id: post.id },
	}));
}

const { id } = Astro.params;

// Rich long-form blog content aligned with Aurorys tone
const blogContentMap: Record<
	string,
	{
		title: string;
		category: string;
		date: string;
		readTime: string;
		prestigeQuote: string;
		prestigeCite: string;
		sections: { id: string; title: string; paragraphs: string[] }[];
		graphicTitle: string;
		graphicColors: string; // gradient classes
		ctaSubject: string;
	}
> = {
	"saas-startup-assessment": {
		title: "How We'd Assess a SaaS Startup: A Hypothetical Walkthrough",
		category: "Methodology",
		date: "May 2026",
		readTime: "6 min read",
		prestigeQuote:
			"We'd rather expose a critical vulnerability today than read about your breach in the news tomorrow.",
		prestigeCite: "The Assessment Principle",
		graphicTitle: "SaaS Threat Model Blueprint",
		graphicColors:
			"from-cyan-500/20 via-blue-500/10 to-transparent border-cyan-500/20",
		ctaSubject: "SOLUTIONS_FIRST_LIGHT",
		sections: [
			{
				id: "introduction",
				title: "Introduction: Standard Audits Are Theater",
				paragraphs: [
					"Most startup security audits are a checkboxes game. An external auditor sends a spreadsheet, your team checks 'Yes' to password complexities, and a certificate is minted. Meanwhile, your production database has a wildcard admin role accessible from any network endpoint, and your developers are committing API keys directly to git.",
					"We do things differently. Here is exactly how we would run a first-principles security posture assessment for a hypothetical SaaS startup.",
					"> Compliance does not equal security. You can pass a SOC 2 audit with flying colors while hosting an entirely exposed network boundary. Real security begins at the infrastructure design layer.",
				],
			},
			{
				id: "step1-identity",
				title: "1. Probe the Identity Perimeter",
				paragraphs: [
					"Our first stop is identity controls. We don't just ask if you have MFA enabled; we verify if your single sign-on (SSO) provider covers your third-party deployment tools and cloud consoles. Wildcard permissions on administrative roles represent a massive attack surface. We audit access boundaries to ensure least-privilege configurations.",
					"Here is an example of a secure, least-privilege IAM policy baseline for a developer role that restricts direct database modifications:",
					'```json\n{\n  "Version": "2012-10-17",\n  "Statement": [\n    {\n      "Effect": "Allow",\n      "Action": [\n        "ec2:Describe*",\n        "rds:Describe*"\n      ],\n      "Resource": "*"\n    },\n    {\n      "Effect": "Deny",\n      "Action": [\n        "rds:DeleteDBInstance",\n        "rds:ModifyDBInstance"\n      ],\n      "Resource": "arn:aws:rds:*:*:db:prod-*"\n    }\n  ]\n}\n```',
					"During our identity review, we audit the following critical nodes:",
					"- Admin dashboard wildcard roles in SSO providers\n- Static access keys committed to developer machines\n- Inactive contractor accounts with active API privileges\n- Multi-factor authentication enforcement exceptions",
				],
			},
			{
				id: "step2-network",
				title: "2. Verify Network Isolation boundaries",
				paragraphs: [
					"Next, we map the network topology. Production database nodes, Redis caches, and admin tooling endpoints should never live on public networks. We check for public access configurations and ensure that database interfaces are securely situated inside private subnets, behind zero-trust access proxies or private VPN gates.",
					'```hcl\n# Terraform network snippet isolating production database\nresource "aws_db_subnet_group" "db_private" {\n  name       = "prod-db-private-subnet-group"\n  subnet_ids = [aws_subnet.private_a.id, aws_subnet.private_b.id]\n\n  tags = {\n    Name = "Isolated DB Subnets"\n  }\n}\n```',
					"> Security Warning: If your database's security group allows 0.0.0.0/0 (even with a secure password), you are one zero-day vulnerability away from total data extraction. Always isolate resources behind private subnets.",
				],
			},
			{
				id: "step3-pipeline",
				title: "3. Check Pipeline & Code Integration",
				paragraphs: [
					"Security isn't a check at release; it is woven into every commit. We audit your CI/CD pipelines to ensure secrets scanning tools are actively configured. Leaving hardcoded API keys in repository branches is the single most common trigger for modern data exposures.",
					"We review how keys and credentials flow from developers to production servers, ensuring that environments rely on short-lived tokens instead of static credentials.",
				],
			},
			{
				id: "conclusion",
				title: "Conclusion: Roadmap Over Checklists",
				paragraphs: [
					"An assessment shouldn't leave you with anxiety. It should leave you with a prioritized, engineering-ready roadmap. In our First Light engagements, we translate findings directly into actionable tickets your team can resolve in sprints.",
				],
			},
		],
	},
	"actionable-assessments": {
		title:
			"How to Make Your Security Assessment Actionable (Instead of Shelf-Worthy)",
		category: "Security",
		date: "May 2026",
		readTime: "4 min read",
		prestigeQuote:
			"A recommendation you can't translate to a commit is just a waste of paper.",
		prestigeCite: "Actionable Security Doctrine",
		graphicTitle: "Audit-to-Ticket Pipeline",
		graphicColors:
			"from-emerald-500/20 via-teal-500/10 to-transparent border-emerald-500/20",
		ctaSubject: "SOLUTIONS_SPRINT",
		sections: [
			{
				id: "the-pdf-trap",
				title: "The PDF Trap",
				paragraphs: [
					"Every security consultant delivers a report. Usually, it's a 150-page PDF filled with generic regulatory speak, compliance tables, and scary-looking risk scores. The founder reads the first five pages, gets overwhelmed, and files it away. The PDF sits on the virtual shelf gathering dust, and the systems remain exactly as vulnerable as before.",
					"To make security work, assessments must be structured as actionable backlogs.",
				],
			},
			{
				id: "ticket-structure",
				title: "Translating Findings to Engineering Tasks",
				paragraphs: [
					"Every security finding should read like an engineering task. Instead of writing 'Database access is insecure,' write a clear specification: 'Restrict PostgreSQL instance security group to allow ingress only from private subnet (10.0.1.0/24).' Provide the exact code snippets or configurations required so developers don't have to guess.",
					"Here is a markdown template we use for creating remediation tickets in client backlogs:",
					'```markdown\n## Title: HARDEN-04: Isolate Production Database Endpoint\n\n### Description\nCurrently, the database accepts direct connections from the public gateway. Restrict access strictly to the web application tier.\n\n### Remediation Steps\n1. Modify `main.tf` under infrastructure repo to remove public accessibility.\n2. Bind security group to web security group only.\n\n### Expected Configuration\n```hcl\nresource "aws_security_group_rule" "db_ingress" {\n  type                     = "ingress"\n  from_port                = 5432\n  to_port                  = 5432\n  protocol                 = "tcp"\n  security_group_id        = aws_security_group.db.id\n  source_security_group_id = aws_security_group.web.id\n}\n```\n```',
				],
			},
			{
				id: "remediation-sprints",
				title: "Run Remediation Sprints",
				paragraphs: [
					"Don't try to fix everything at once. Focus on remediation sprints: group tickets by context (e.g., identity first, network boundary second) and resolve them in 2-week sprints. Bounding the effort keeps engineering teams focused.",
					"- Sprint 1: Identity & SSO Cleanup\n- Sprint 2: Network zoning and database isolation\n- Sprint 3: CI/CD Pipeline secrets detection & automated tests",
				],
			},
		],
	},
	"blueprint-model": {
		title:
			"The Blueprint Model: Why We Deliver Architecture, Not Just Recommendations",
		category: "Methodology",
		date: "May 2026",
		readTime: "5 min read",
		prestigeQuote:
			"True security is a design property, not an afterthought checklist.",
		prestigeCite: "Design Principles",
		graphicTitle: "Architecture Blueprint Scheme",
		graphicColors:
			"from-violet-500/20 via-purple-500/10 to-transparent border-violet-500/20",
		ctaSubject: "SOLUTIONS_FOUNDATION",
		sections: [
			{
				id: "consulting-flaws",
				title: "The Flaws of Traditional Security Consulting",
				paragraphs: [
					"Standard consultancies operate on recommendations: they analyze, find problems, write down suggestions, and hand them off. But writing 'use infrastructure-as-code' isn't helpful unless you also supply the baseline repository templates to start from.",
					"We believe security is built through design and blueprints.",
					"> Recommendations without code are just chores. Blueprints are deliverables that add capacity to your team from day one.",
				],
			},
			{
				id: "blueprint-philosophy",
				title: "What is a Security Blueprint?",
				paragraphs: [
					"A security blueprint is production-ready architecture. It includes detailed system designs, threat models, hardened templates (e.g., Terraform, Pulumi, or Docker configs), and step-by-step guides. We deliver configurations your engineers can clone and deploy immediately.",
					"Here is an example of a reusable, hardened baseline Dockerfile blueprint we deliver for Node.js microservices:",
					'```dockerfile\n# Hardened Node.js runtime blueprint\nFROM node:20-alpine AS builder\nWORKDIR /usr/src/app\nCOPY package*.json ./\nRUN npm ci --only=production\nCOPY . .\n\nFROM gcr.io/distroless/nodejs20-debian12\nWORKDIR /usr/src/app\nCOPY --from=builder /usr/src/app .\nUSER 10001\nEXPOSE 8080\nCMD ["server.js"]\n```',
					"This configuration eliminates root privileges and removes standard shell binaries, dramatically reducing the potential attack surface.",
				],
			},
			{
				id: "retaining-keys",
				title: "You Own the Baseline",
				paragraphs: [
					"Blueprints ensure you retain sovereignty over your infrastructure. We don't manage your servers. We deploy the blueprints, train your team on how they work, and transfer full ownership.",
					"- Production-ready Terraform architectures\n- Zero-trust remote access controls\n- Automated backup and recovery scripts\n- Hardened service configurations",
				],
			},
		],
	},
	"transparency-security": {
		title: "Why We Don't Guarantee Security (And Why That's Honest, Not Lazy)",
		category: "Methodology",
		date: "May 2026",
		readTime: "4 min read",
		prestigeQuote: "Absolute security is a myth. Resilience is real.",
		prestigeCite: "The Sovereignty Thesis",
		graphicTitle: "Resilience Bounds Analysis",
		graphicColors:
			"from-rose-500/20 via-pink-500/10 to-transparent border-rose-500/20",
		ctaSubject: "SOLUTIONS_FULL_CONSTELLATION",
		sections: [
			{
				id: "honesty-in-security",
				title: "The Honest Truth About Risk",
				paragraphs: [
					"If a security consultant guarantees that your systems will never be breached, they are lying or selling you insurance. Absolute protection does not exist in network security. Adversaries change, new software vulnerabilities emerge, and human configurations can drift.",
					"An honest approach focuses on residual risk and operational resilience.",
					"> There are two types of organizations: those who have been compromised, and those who do not yet know they are compromised. Focus on minimizing the impact of an compromise rather than assuming it will never happen.",
				],
			},
			{
				id: "resilience-properties",
				title: "Resilience Over Guarantees",
				paragraphs: [
					"Resilience means your systems can withstand failures, restrict lateral movement, and recover immediately. If an endpoint is compromised, network zoning restricts access to other zones. If a server is corrupted, an immutable snapshot allows Day-0 recovery in minutes.",
					"A key element of resilience is automated snapshot synchronization. Here is an example of an rsync cron script blueprint for data synchronization:",
					'```bash\n#!/bin/bash\n# Hardened snapshot sync script\nset -euo pipefail\n\nSRC_DIR="/var/lib/prod-data"\nDEST_DIR="admin@backup-node.internal:/backup/snapshots/"\n\nrsync -avz --delete --bwlimit=10000 \\\n  -e "ssh -i /etc/ssh/backup_key -o StrictHostKeyChecking=yes" \\\n  "$SRC_DIR" "$DEST_DIR"\n```',
				],
			},
			{
				id: "sovereign-control",
				title: "True Ownership of Risks",
				paragraphs: [
					"We help you understand residual risks so you can make informed decisions. We don't hide findings behind compliance jargon; we outline them directly so your engineers can actively monitor and maintain control.",
					"- Map the potential impact of vulnerabilities\n- Establish clear isolation points\n- Enable fast recovery protocols\n- Train team members on response procedures",
				],
			},
		],
	},
	"startup-quick-wins": {
		title:
			"5 Things Every Startup Should Do This Week for Security (That Cost Nothing)",
		category: "Security",
		date: "May 2026",
		readTime: "5 min read",
		prestigeQuote: "Lock your doors before you start buying vault-grade locks.",
		prestigeCite: "Hygiene Priority",
		graphicTitle: "Day-0 Security Wins Checklist",
		graphicColors:
			"from-amber-500/20 via-yellow-500/10 to-transparent border-amber-500/20",
		ctaSubject: "SOLUTIONS_CLEARANCE",
		sections: [
			{
				id: "budget-myths",
				title: "The Budget Myth",
				paragraphs: [
					"Many early-stage teams believe security is a luxury that requires expensive software, compliance frameworks, or dedicated hires. But the vast majority of cybersecurity compromises target simple, basic hygiene failures that cost nothing to resolve.",
				],
			},
			{
				id: "five-wins",
				title: "The 5 Essential Free Wins",
				paragraphs: [
					"Here are 5 security hygiene improvements that cost nothing but time to set up:",
					"- 1. Enforce Multi-Factor Authentication (MFA) across your team on SSO and admin portals.\n- 2. Integrate a secrets scanning tool in git pipelines to catch hardcoded secrets before commits reach remote branches.\n- 3. Remove public access endpoints from databases and Redis layers, keeping them strictly inside private subnets.\n- 4. Enforce encrypted, automatic backups of production databases stored securely in a separate region.\n- 5. Write down a basic recovery plan detailing who handles communications and what gets shut down during an incident.",
					"For Win #2, here is a GitHub Actions workflow snippet that integrates GitLeaks to detect hardcoded API keys on every pull request:",
					"```yaml\nname: Security Scan\non: [pull_request]\njobs:\n  gitleaks:\n    runs-on: ubuntu-latest\n    steps:\n      - uses: actions/checkout@v4\n        with:\n          fetch-depth: 0\n      - name: Run Gitleaks\n        uses: gitleaks/gitleaks-action@v2\n        env:\n          GITHUB_TOKEN: ${{ secrets.GITHUB_TOKEN }}\n```",
				],
			},
			{
				id: "the-first-commit",
				title: "Build Habits Early",
				paragraphs: [
					"Securing a system with 5 employees is simple. Securing a system after you scale to 50 employees is a massive refactoring project. Set the habits early, starting with your first infrastructure code configurations.",
				],
			},
		],
	},
	"zero-trust-guide": {
		title: "Zero-Trust Architecture for Startups: A Practical Guide",
		category: "Security",
		date: "May 2026",
		readTime: "5 min read",
		prestigeQuote: "Never trust. Always verify. The perimeter is dead.",
		prestigeCite: "Zero-Trust Doctrine",
		graphicTitle: "Zero-Trust Isolation Path",
		graphicColors:
			"from-cyan-500/20 via-emerald-500/10 to-transparent border-cyan-500/20",
		ctaSubject: "SOLUTIONS_BEACON",
		sections: [
			{
				id: "perimeter-dead",
				title: "The Perimeter is Dead",
				paragraphs: [
					"Startups traditionally built a network perimeter: a firewall around the office or a VPN around the cloud, assuming anyone inside was safe. But in a remote-first world utilizing third-party SaaS tools, this perimeter does not exist. Trusting connections based solely on network location is a recipe for disaster.",
					"Zero-trust requires that every access request be authenticated, authorized, and continuously validated.",
				],
			},
			{
				id: "implementing-zt",
				title: "Implementing Zero-Trust Access controls",
				paragraphs: [
					"To implement zero-trust, start by routing administrative services behind an identity-aware proxy (like Authelia, Pomerium, or Cloudflare Access). This ensures that database consoles and admin portals are not accessible without SSO authentication.",
					"Here is an example Nginx proxy configuration that enforces authorization checks against an authentication daemon:",
					'```nginx\n# Nginx routing with zero-trust validation header\nserver {\n    listen 443 ssl;\n    server_name admin.internal.company.com;\n\n    location / {\n        auth_request /auth-check;\n        proxy_pass http://internal-admin-dashboard:8080;\n    }\n\n    location = /auth-check {\n        internal;\n        proxy_pass http://auth-service.internal:9090/verify;\n        proxy_pass_request_body off;\n        proxy_set_header Content-Length "";\n    }\n}\n```',
				],
			},
			{
				id: "key-benefits",
				title: "Key Implementation Milestones",
				paragraphs: [
					"An effective zero-trust architecture can be deployed incrementally. Focus on these milestones first:",
					"- SSO integration for all internal development tools\n- Context-aware access rules (limiting logins to verified developer IPs)\n- Eliminating static SSH keys in favor of ephemeral certificate authorities\n- Isolating build runners and staging environments",
				],
			},
		],
	},
	"wireguard-tunnels": {
		title: "Hardening Admin Portals with WireGuard VPN Tunnels",
		category: "Technology",
		date: "May 2026",
		readTime: "6 min read",
		prestigeQuote:
			"If your administrative interface is accessible from the internet, it is already compromised.",
		prestigeCite: "Infrastructure Hardening Protocol",
		graphicTitle: "WireGuard Tunnel Scheme",
		graphicColors:
			"from-blue-500/20 via-indigo-500/10 to-transparent border-blue-500/20",
		ctaSubject: "SOLUTIONS_SURGE",
		sections: [
			{
				id: "isolation-why",
				title: "Why Public Admin Portals are a Liability",
				paragraphs: [
					"Hosting your internal administrative dashboard or database console on a public IP exposes you to brute-force attacks, port scans, and zero-day web vulnerability exploits. Standard password authentication or IP whitelisting is not sufficient.",
					"The safest configuration is complete network isolation: bind admin ports to local interfaces and route connections through a private WireGuard VPN tunnel.",
				],
			},
			{
				id: "wireguard-config",
				title: "WireGuard Server Configuration",
				paragraphs: [
					"WireGuard is a fast, lightweight, and modern VPN protocol. Here is a secure server configuration file (`/etc/wireguard/wg0.conf`) blueprint that routes only admin traffic:",
					"```ini\n[Interface]\nPrivateKey = SERVER_PRIVATE_KEY\nAddress = 10.8.0.1/24\nListenPort = 51820\n\n# PostUp and PostDown commands for packet forwarding rules\nPostUp = iptables -A FORWARD -i wg0 -j ACCEPT; iptables -t nat -A POSTROUTING -o eth0 -j MASQUERADE\nPostDown = iptables -D FORWARD -i wg0 -j ACCEPT; iptables -t nat -D POSTROUTING -o eth0 -j MASQUERADE\n\n[Peer]\nPublicKey = DEVELOPER_PUBLIC_KEY\nAllowedIPs = 10.8.0.2/32\n```",
					"This configuration creates an isolated VPN subnet (`10.8.0.0/24`) where developer machines connect securely over UDP port 51820.",
				],
			},
			{
				id: "routing-rules",
				title: "Enforcing Routing Isolation",
				paragraphs: [
					"Once the tunnel is active, configure your admin applications to listen strictly on the VPN interface IP, preventing any external queries from reaching the daemon.",
					"```bash\n# Bind node dashboard service to VPN IP only\nnode server.js --host 10.8.0.1 --port 8080\n```",
					"> Security Tip: Regularly rotate WireGuard peer configurations and automate host updates to ensure the tunnel endpoints remain secure.",
				],
			},
		],
	},
	"podman-docker-hardening": {
		title: "Rootless Podman vs Hardened Docker: Container Security Tradeoffs",
		category: "Technology",
		date: "May 2026",
		readTime: "5 min read",
		prestigeQuote:
			"Root privileges inside a container represent root privileges on the host server.",
		prestigeCite: "Container Isolation Doctrine",
		graphicTitle: "Container Privilege Map",
		graphicColors:
			"from-purple-500/20 via-pink-500/10 to-transparent border-purple-500/20",
		ctaSubject: "SOLUTIONS_SURGE",
		sections: [
			{
				id: "container-risks",
				title: "The Container Privilege Problem",
				paragraphs: [
					"By default, the Docker daemon runs with root privileges. If a containerized application is compromised and has root privileges inside the container, an attacker can exploit namespace configuration errors or kernel vulnerabilities to escape to the host server.",
					"Hardening container environments is critical to maintaining tenant isolation.",
				],
			},
			{
				id: "rootless-podman",
				title: "Option A: Rootless Podman Runtimes",
				paragraphs: [
					"Podman provides a rootless daemon configuration that uses user namespaces to map container root permissions to a non-privileged user on the host. If a container is breached, the attacker remains sandboxed with no privileges on the host.",
					"Here is an example command showing how to run a rootless container using Podman, mapping host user ports and dropping core privileges:",
					"```bash\n# Running rootless container dropping capability privileges\npodman run -d --name secure-web \\\n  --cap-drop=ALL --cap-add=NET_BIND_SERVICE \\\n  -p 8080:8080 \\\n  docker.io/library/nginx:alpine\n```",
				],
			},
			{
				id: "hardened-docker",
				title: "Option B: Hardened Docker configurations",
				paragraphs: [
					"If you must use Docker for pipeline compatibility, you can configure daemon-level rules to deny root access and restrict runtime policies.",
					"Apply these default hardening configurations to `/etc/docker/daemon.json`:",
					'```json\n{\n  "no-new-privileges": true,\n  "userns-remap": "default",\n  "live-restore": true,\n  "icc": false\n}\n```',
					"This locks down Docker containers, separating container user namespaces, denying privilege escalation (`no-new-privileges`), and disabling inter-container communication (`icc: false`) by default.",
				],
			},
		],
	},
};

const post = blogContentMap[id] || blogContentMap["saas-startup-assessment"];
const postMeta = blogPosts.find((p) => p.id === id) || blogPosts[0];
const postTags = postMeta?.tags || [];
---

<BaseLayout title={`${post.title} | Blog | Aurorys Labs`}>
  <div class="fixed inset-0 -z-20">
    <div
      class="w-full h-full"
      style="background-image: url('/images/astrophotography/astro-image11.webp'); background-size: cover; background-position: center;"
    ></div>
    <div class="absolute inset-0 bg-gradient-to-b from-[var(--bg-primary)]/40 via-[var(--bg-primary)]/35 to-[var(--bg-primary)]/75"></div>
  </div>

  <AuroraOverlay client:load />
  <Navbar client:load />
  <MobileNav client:load />

  {/* Article Header */}
  <section class="relative z-10 pt-32 pb-12 md:pt-40 md:pb-16">
    <div class="content-width mx-auto px-6 text-center">
      <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto space-y-4">
        <div class="flex items-center justify-center gap-3 text-xs font-mono">
          <span class="text-[var(--aurora-green-solid)] font-semibold uppercase tracking-wider">{post.category}</span>
          <span class="text-white/40">•</span>
          <span class="text-white/60">{post.date}</span>
          <span class="text-white/40">•</span>
          <span class="text-white/60">{post.readTime}</span>
        </div>
        <h1 class="font-sans font-bold text-3xl md:text-5xl lg:text-6xl text-[var(--text-stellar)] tracking-tight leading-tight mb-6">
          {post.title}
        </h1>
        {postTags.length > 0 && (
          <div class="flex flex-wrap justify-center gap-1.5 pt-2">
            {postTags.map((tag) => (
              <span class="backdrop-blur-sm text-[10px] px-2.5 py-0.5 rounded-full border border-white/10 bg-white/[0.03] text-white/60 font-mono font-medium">
                #{tag}
              </span>
            ))}
          </div>
        )}
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  {/* Article Content Layout */}
  <section class="relative z-10 py-8 border-t border-white/[0.04]">
    <div class="content-width px-6">
      <div class="grid grid-cols-1 lg:grid-cols-12 gap-10 items-start">

        {/* Sticky Sidebar Navigation Table of Contents */}
        <div class="lg:col-span-3 lg:sticky lg:top-28 hidden lg:block">
          <TableOfContents
            items={post.sections.map((sec) => ({
              id: sec.id,
              label: sec.title.split(": ").length > 1 ? sec.title.split(": ")[1] : sec.title,
            }))}
            client:load
          />
        </div>

        {/* Main Content Reading Panel */}
        <div class="lg:col-span-9 space-y-16">

          <div class="glass-card p-8 md:p-12 rounded-3xl border border-white/[0.06] bg-[rgba(13,17,23,0.3)] space-y-8 font-sans text-white/95 leading-relaxed text-left text-base">

            {/* Dynamic CSS/SVG Graphic Placeholder */}
            <div class={`w-full h-48 md:h-64 rounded-2xl border bg-gradient-to-br ${post.graphicColors} flex flex-col items-center justify-center relative overflow-hidden group mb-8`}>
              <div class="absolute inset-0 bg-grid-pattern opacity-10 pointer-events-none"></div>
              <div class="absolute w-24 h-24 rounded-full bg-[var(--aurora-green-solid)]/10 blur-2xl group-hover:scale-125 transition-transform duration-500 pointer-events-none"></div>
              <div class="text-center space-y-3 relative z-10 px-4">
                <div class="text-[10px] font-mono font-bold tracking-widest text-[var(--text-muted)] uppercase">
                  Infographic Placeholder
                </div>
                <div class="text-base md:text-lg font-bold text-[var(--text-stellar)]">
                  {post.graphicTitle}
                </div>
                <p class="text-xs text-white/40 max-w-sm mx-auto">
                  (Final SVG logo grid will be integrated here upon assets upload)
                </p>
              </div>
            </div>

            {post.sections.map((section) => (
              <div id={section.id} class="scroll-mt-28 space-y-4">
                <h2 class="font-sans font-bold text-2xl tracking-tight text-[var(--text-stellar)] border-b border-white/[0.04] pb-2 mt-8">
                  {section.title}
                </h2>
                {section.paragraphs.map((p) => {
                  if (p.startsWith("```")) {
                    const lines = p.split("\n");
                    const lang = lines[0].replace("```", "").trim();
                    const code = lines.slice(1, lines.length - 1).join("\n");
                    return (
                      <pre class="bg-black/40 p-4 md:p-6 rounded-2xl border border-white/10 font-mono text-xs overflow-x-auto text-[var(--aurora-green-solid)] my-6 relative leading-relaxed max-w-full">
                        {lang && <span class="absolute top-2.5 right-3 text-[9px] uppercase text-white/35 tracking-widest font-sans font-bold">{lang}</span>}
                        <code class="block whitespace-pre select-all">{code}</code>
                      </pre>
                    );
                  }
                  if (p.startsWith("> ")) {
                    return (
                      <div class="my-6 p-5 rounded-2xl border border-emerald-500/20 bg-emerald-500/5 text-sm md:text-base leading-relaxed text-white/90 border-l-4 border-l-[var(--aurora-green-solid)]">
                        {p.substring(2)}
                      </div>
                    );
                  }
                  if (p.startsWith("- ")) {
                    const items = p.split("\n").map(item => item.replace(/^- /, "").trim());
                    return (
                      <ul class="list-disc pl-6 my-6 space-y-2.5 text-white/80 text-sm md:text-base">
                        {items.map(item => <li>{item}</li>)}
                      </ul>
                    );
                  }
                  return (
                    <p class="text-white/80 text-sm md:text-base leading-relaxed my-4">
                      {p}
                    </p>
                  );
                })}
              </div>
            ))}

            {/* Prestige Statement Block */}
            <div class="py-12 my-8 relative overflow-hidden rounded-2xl border border-white/[0.04] bg-white/[0.01] px-6 text-center">
              <div class="absolute inset-0 bg-[var(--aurora-green-solid)]/5 blur-3xl opacity-30 rounded-full" />
              <blockquote class="font-serif italic text-2xl md:text-3xl text-[var(--text-stellar)] max-w-2xl mx-auto relative z-10 leading-snug">
                "{post.prestigeQuote}"
              </blockquote>
              <cite class="block mt-4 text-xs font-sans text-[var(--text-muted)] tracking-wider uppercase font-semibold not-italic relative z-10">
                — {post.prestigeCite}
              </cite>
            </div>

          </div>

          {/* Quick Back to Blog */}
          <div class="flex justify-start">
            <a
              href="/blog"
              class="inline-flex items-center gap-2 text-sm font-semibold text-[var(--aurora-green-solid)] hover:text-white transition-colors cursor-pointer"
            >
              <svg class="w-4 h-4" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5">
                <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M10 19l-7-7m0 0l7-7m-7 7h18" />
              </svg>
              Return to Insights list
            </a>
          </div>

        </div>

      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <ContactSection />
  <Footer />
</BaseLayout>
